Perittia piperatella is a moth of the family Elachistidae. It is found on the Iberian Peninsula.
The wingspan is 8.5â€“10 mm.The larvae feed on Cistus ladanifer. They mine the leaves of their host plant. The mine has the form of a large, strongly puckered, tentiform mine at the leaf margin and usually at the leaf tip. Pupation takes place inside the mine, but not in a cocoon. Larvae can be found from November to March.